<br>
You round up four, snare, and one or two resist.<br>
<br>
What to do?<br>
<br>
Here's how I handle it.  First, leave the snared boys and girls behind and continue to run in a straight line away from them with the uncooperative critters in tow.<br>
<br>
Second, make sure you have that unsnared critter or two targeted.  Often, I find it's the snared beasties I had on target so I need to either do a quick turn-around and hit F8 or hit F9 and manually target that Wyvern closest to me.<br>
<br>
Third, get your distance as quickly as possible, turn, and re-cast BoF or Atol's.  I'm using Atol's now exclusively.<br>
<br>
If it sticks, great.  If not, try to head in another direction that doesn't take you too far from the already snared grouping, in a straight line, and re-do the steps above.<br>
<br>
Once you've snared this last critter, depending on how much time has past you can do one of two things:  One, simply round all four back together.  I get in the direct middle of the last snared guy and the others that are snared and let them walk to me.  Then, I make a V-formation with them and then I circle around them as close as possible.<br>
<br>
I get hit often at this stage because you have to circle close.  I've been killed at this stage too.  Hey, it happens.<br>
<br>
Always, always, always Re-BoF after you round them.  If one resists, re-Bof again.  You can tell if they've all gotten snared by the order.  If you get a:<br>
<br>
     snared<br>
     resist<br>
     snared<br>
     snared<br>
<br>
and then after the next BoF<br>
<br>
     resist<br>
     snared<br>
     snared<br>
     snared<br>
<br>
then  you know all were re-snared.  The ones that resisted were snared.  The order is always the same, so if one resists and is snared on the next cast, then he's snared.<br>
<br>
Now, if a lot of time passed between the intial snaring and the snare of the last critter, then quickly run back to the other three and re-snare them.  Then, round them up again, then re-snare them all again.<br>
<br>
Yep.  That's what it takes.  Atol's lasts longer, but I always resnare.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uennyaorcsbane.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ennya Orcsbane</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(8/15/01 7:33:03 am)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: My main problem with quadding.......</span><hr size=1> I get resisted all to often by ONE mob. I disagree that there is rhyme or reason to it, I usually grab 2 walruses and 2 ulthorks, or 1 and 3 either way. Which resists is never predictable except taht the Ulthork hunters SEEM to resist BoF Less. When I get a resist, it is almost always one. I wil usually run far enough away to BoF it, and repeat till it's snared. If I get it on the first recast, I round them, up, and start slamming them till I see the BoF drop. I do NOT bother re-snaring when they are together. I still usually get one resist and now it's REALLY hard to predict which one it is.<br>
<br>
When BoF drops, I stop Damaging and wait till the other BoF dropps and re round up.  Usually the BoF isn't resisted this time, dont know why, but I have a running theory that damaged mobs resist less.<br>
<br>
I also have another theory, but I'm sticking it in another thread. <p>Ennya Orcsbane<BR>
1st Elder of The Tears Of Veeshan<BR>
Advanced Slayer, WurnSlayer<BR>
Assigner of the Hunt<BR>
Wizardess<BR></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/unoonanie.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Noonanie</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(8/15/01 9:13:41 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: My main problem with quadding.......</span><hr size=1> Your solution really depends on the circumstance...<br>
<br>
I believe you should round yer mobs up first... then cast BoF.<br>
Atol's is a fine spell... but the mana cost is more... and you<br>
don't really recieve much extra benefit from it.  And if yer<br>
running pretty close to OOM... BoF is the way to go.<br>
Especially in this scenario when yer getting a lot of resists.<br>
<br>
If BoF is resisted... it's all dependant on how many resisted.<br>
<br>
If only 1 resist... target the resistant bastage... move in a<br>
straight line away from the rest of the group to make space...<br>
then cast Tishan's Clash.  Click yer Staff of Temperate Flux to<br>
get yer gems up, while moving away to make space again...<br>
then recast BoF.  If ya timed it right... the remaining 3 mobs<br>
that were previously snared should be catching up.  This is<br>
why you run in that straight line... so the snared mobs have<br>
the chance to catch up... and get snared again.  If yer<br>
good... you'll have just resnared the entire group...  and only<br>
a small amount of touch up is necessary before nuking away.<br>
<br>
Aye... ya might get a lil beat up... but that's why you use<br>
Tishan's Clash... pretty fast casting... yer channeling should<br>
be pretty decent... and if yer really worried... use yer skin.<br>
Unless they resist the Clash too... mob has 1 chance at<br>
dealing dmg to you.<br>
<br>
If more than 1 resists... run away.  Make sure you create<br>
space.  They'll still be following you... and that's what ya<br>
want.  Keep in mind the resisted ones that you left behind.<br>
Just double back and basically &quot;Do Over!!!&quot;  Round em all up<br>
after you get them all snared.<br>
<br>
Generally, rounding them up can be a bother.  Most important<br>
thing is... know where you can and cannot move.  Just find<br>
the mid point between yer snared mobs.  They'll come to you.<br>
Once you start getting nervous.... circle them around and find<br>
the mid point again...<br>
<br>
Getting them on the same snare timer is pretty important.  It<br>
comes down to efficiency.  It's all about killing them fast... if<br>
ya gotta dilly dally with em in the beginning and ya gotta dilly<br>
dally with em in the end... it's taking you a long time to kill the<br>
stupid things... very unwizardly...  Just stowe the ego and the<br>
testosterone... just resnare and get on with it.<br>
<br>
Gluck.<br>
<br>
Lasservien Leadbottom<br>
lvl 59 Evoker - Silent Shadow<br>
